However, beyond this we do not know much about the detailed morphology of
 these cells, how many synapses do they have, who are their synaptic partners.
 We do not yet know if position sensitive cells synapses onto each other,
 although indirect evidence would suggest that they do (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Aksay:2003un,Dale:2015hh"

\end_inset

).
 To answer some of these question, we chose to perform serial electron microscop
y on position sensitive cells in the hindbrain of larval zebrafish.
 The larval zebrafish is believed to have ~100 integrator neurons unilaterally,
 which makes such a system amenable to large scale imaging efforts, and
 that the organization of these cells in the larval animal might most likely
 be conserved in the adult (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "gilland_hindbrain_2014"

\end_inset

).
 This analysis reveled that the existence of at least three groups of neurons
 that were part of the unilateral integrator.
 We found neurons with ipsilateral axons that gave rise to collaterals within
 the same dendritic field as other integrator neurons.
 Apart from the previously know ipsilateral and contralateral projections
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Lee:2015dv"

\end_inset

), we found few neurons with both ipsi and contralateral projections.
 Distribution of synaptic locations of both pre and post synapses for all
 neurons revealed on average these cells received three time more input
 than output.
 We can extend the significance of these findings by inferring the neurotransmit
ter identity of these neurons based on the location of the cells bodies,
 as they are known to express glutamate and GABA in alternative stripe like
 patterns in the hindbrain (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Kinkhabwala:2011et"

\end_inset

).
 Doing so, suggests that the cells with ipsilaterally projecting axons and
 collaterals is excitatory, cells with contralatrally projecting axons are
 inhibitory.
 The remaining groups are presumably putative glutamatergic and glycenergic
 neurons.
 These results suggest that the neural integration is achieved by positive
 excitatory feedback unilaterally, and by mutual inhibition contralaterally.
